or=#201040;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="1099" y="1897" width="359" height="140" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Person-affecting&lt;br&gt;view&lt;br&gt;[1+2+5+6+8+14+17]&lt;br&gt;→ AI safety (Redwood Research)&lt;br&gt;   80 lives-eq/$1k · 4% best&lt;br&gt;   runner-up The Humane League · 93%&lt;br&gt;(Jan Narveson, Melinda Roberts)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + future_humans_matter_with_discounting + no_discounting_future_humans + suffering_focused + time_of_perils_exit + person_affecting_view&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Person-affecting population ethics: making happy people is neutral, so the astronomical case for x-risk reduction — which rests on the sheer number of extra future lives saved from extinction — loses almost all its force. Only the harm to people who exist regardless still counts. This is the standard premise longtermism&#x27;s critics deny (discussed as the key objection in Greaves &amp; MacAskill&#x27;s &#x27;The Case for Strong Longtermism&#x27;). It requires no_discounting_future_humans, the astronomical-stakes move it pushes back on. || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 5 future_humans_matter_with_discounting → 6 no_discounting_future_humans → 8 suffering_focused → 14 time_of_perils_exit → 17 person_affecting_view" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJy9WWtv2zgW%2FSsXwc6u3XEcyW8nmwUyjTNTbPpAku5g0BQuLdE2J7KoJaU4nk772%2FeQlGw5UVB3DcyXQKHIc8998l7580HIpyyL0pcy5AfHB0dHdHp6SjeKiZhSSYFif6zwsIzpNmt5foeWUkXhveBLWvrj1rg77o0HY78z9vtU06lMyO%2FXDcZtDKwzrbNFkgoZUzAH5DF5lDAlg7lgkUH0hy3yacrUmC3ZajzPFizWxYsWsVgsWKTHWi74cs7S4k2XplmaKZ4fGC9YmnI1Xop0Pg6FDmQWpyKeFdt7FMvy%2BnjrdLFrQDqbTrmyG2SQaR6uKXYoFQs%2BltNxgg1gxB%2FEmg1Ux6qW8ZjhfGAlGAtZE4xYMCe2sYPQxOjdKp3jeSoiTjD05rU%2BotToycJQN0hxeEfEXJNUFkzxQ5iPLTi0FRrr6Zw7y%2F5DwyRxYDFOKJCLRGpjgfUGnI1DDkQsCW3RdMrikEUy5rSA%2B6MmfVp7d3T%2FyVA1x%2FlDAqVw8J5FGSc5tQibQGhasJ%2B4TmmSrSgzYsxBzcuKHdPZK9JsytMV1a54uJQypCtsYi